  DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN

    The mmaaiillxx(1) utility is an electronic mail processing utility that is
    similar to a line editor for mail, except that lines are replaced by
    messages. The mmaaiillxx(1) utility has two basic modes of operation: reading
    mail and sending mail. Each mode has its own commands and options. The
    first synopsis line above is for sending mail.

    To send mail, give the command mmaaiillxx(1) and one or more login names (for
    users on the same computer) or e-mail addresses. The mmaaiillxx(1) utility
    prompts for a message (unless one has been supplied with the --ss option),
    and then enters input mode. All text typed into mmaaiillxx(1) form part of the
    message until you enter the end-of-file character or the command ~~... See
    "Sending and replying to mail" for a longer discussion; see Tilde/Escapes
    for a list of the commands used in input mode.

    To read mail, give the command mmaaiillxx(1). The mmaaiillxx(1) utility displays a
    list of message headers, each representing a message in your system
    mailbox. In this mode, you can read, save, and delete mail messages. You
    can also reply or send mail (dropping into input mode to do so), and set
    options to control the behavior of mmaaiillxx(1).

    The mmaaiillxx(1) utility takes the following options:
    --bblist
        Send blind carbon copies to list. List should be a comma-separated
        list of names. Normally, all recipients can see who was sent a copy of
        the message. That information is suppressed in a blind carbon copy,
        however, so that only the sender and the blind carbon-copy recipient
        know about the copy.
    --cclist
        Send carbon copies to list of users.

    --ee
        Check for mail in the system mailbox and exit without printing a
        message. If there is mail in the system mailbox, mmaaiillxx(1) returns an
        exit status of 0; otherwise, it returns an exit status of 1. In a
        shell script or a startup file such as ..pprrooffiillee, this is useful for
        checking for the presence of mail.
    --ff[[mbox]]
        Read in the contents of your mmbbooxx (or the specified file) for
        processing; when you qquuiitt, mmaaiillxx(1) writes undeleted messages back to
        this file.

    --HH
        Write a header summary only; this is only the first set of 18
        messages, starting with the first unread message.

    --ii
        Ignore tty interrupt signals. This is particularly useful when using
        mmaaiillxx(1) on noisy phone lines. You can also set this behavior inside
        mmaaiillxx(1) with the ignore option.

    --II
        Run mmaaiillxx(1) in interactive mode even when input is not a terminal. In
        particular, the tilde (~~) special character, when sending mail, is
        only active in interactive mode.

    --nn
        Inhibits reading the system startup files //eettcc//mmaaiill..rrcc and //eettcc//
        mmaaiillxx..rrcc upon startup.

    --NN
        Inhibit the initial display of message headers when reading mail or
        editing a mail folder.
    --sssubject
        Specify subject on command line. (Only the first argument after the --
        ss flag is used as a subject; be sure to quote subjects containing
        spaces.)
    --uuuser
        Is equivalent to:
        mailx -f /var/mail/user
        You must have the appropriate permissions to read mail for user.

    --vv
        Verbose mode. The details of delivery are displayed on the user's
        terminal.

  SSeennddiinngg mmaaiill

    To send a message to one or more people, mmaaiillxx(1) can be invoked with
    arguments that are the names of people to whom the mail will be sent. You
    are then expected to type in your message, followed by a CTRL+D at the
    beginning of a line. The section "Replying to or originating mail"
    describes some features of mmaaiillxx(1) you can use to compose messages.

    An e-mail address can be either a local address or an Internet-style
    address. Internet-style addresses are of the form name@domain; all other
    addresses are taken as local addresses. (The mmaaiillxx(1) utility does not
    recognize UNIX-to-UNIX [UUCP]-style bang addresses or the %-hack.)

  RReeaaddiinngg mmaaiill

    To read mail, give mmaaiillxx(1) no arguments. It checks your mail out of the
    post office, then prints out a one-line header for each message found.
    Each message is numbered, and the message your commands affect is called
    the current message. When you start mmaaiillxx(1), the current message is the
    first message, message 1. You can display the message using the pprriinntt
    command (which can be abbreviated pp). To make a new message the current
    message, use the commands ++ and -- to move backwards and forwards in the
    list, or specify a message by number. There are other ways of specifying
    which messages your commands will act on; see "Specifying messages."

  DDiissppoossiinngg ooff mmaaiill

    After you examine a message, you can ddeelleettee (dd the message or rreeppllyy (rr) to
    it. Deletion causes the mmaaiillxx(1) program to forget about the message. This
    is not irreversible; the message can be uunnddeelleetteedd (uu) by giving its
    number; or the mmaaiillxx(1) session can be aborted by giving the eexxiitt (xx)
    command (rather than the usual qquuiitt command). Usually, deleted messages
    completely disappear.

  SSppeecciiffyyiinngg mmeessssaaggeess

    Commands such as pprriinntt and ddeelleettee can be given a list of message numbers
    as arguments to apply to a number of messages at once. Thus, ddeelleettee 11 22
    deletes messages 1 and 2; ddeelleettee 11--55 deletes messages 1 through 5. The
    special name ** addresses all messages, and $$ addresses the last message.
    The command ttoopp, which prints the first few lines of a message, could be
    used in ttoopp ** to print the first few lines of all messages.

    Following is a list of message specifications and their explanations:

    num
        Message number num
    n--m
        Messages number n through m

    **
        All messages

    ..
        The current message

    ++
        The following appropriate message

    --
        The previous appropriate message

    ^^
        The first appropriate message in the list

    $$
        The last message in the list

    address
        All messages from address (as shown in the header)
    //string
        All messages with string in the subject line (case is ignored)
    ::c
        All messages of type c, where c is one of the following:

        dd
            Deleted messages

        nn
            New messages

        oo
            Old messages (messages that are unread or new)

        rr
            Read messages

        uu
            Unread messages

    The word "appropriate" is needed because although most commands work only
    on undeleted commands, the uunnddeelleettee command only works on deleted
    commands. So pprriinntt ^^ prints the first undeleted message in the list;
    uunnddeelleettee ^^ undeletes the first deleted message in the list.

  SSeennddiinngg nneeww mmaaiill oorr rreeppllyyiinngg ttoo mmaaiill

    You can use the rreeppllyy command to set up a response to a message, sending
    it back to the person who sent it to you. The text you then type in, up to
    an end-of-file, defines the contents of the message. While you are
    composing a message, mmaaiillxx(1) treats lines beginning with the tilde
    character (~~) specially. For instance, typing ~~mm (alone on a line) will
    place a copy of the current message into the response, right shifting it
    by a tab stop (see indentprefix variable later in this topic). Other
    escapes will set up subject fields, add and delete recipients to the
    message, and allow you to escape to an editor to revise the message or to
    a shell to run some commands. (These options are given in the summary that
    follows.)

  EEnnddiinngg aa mmaaiill--pprroocceessssiinngg sseessssiioonn

    You can end a mmaaiillxx(1) session with the qquuiitt (qq) command. Messages that
    have been examined go to your mbox file unless they have been deleted, in
    which case they are discarded. Unexamined messages go back to the post
    office. (See the --ff option discussed previously in this topic.)

